6,000 for the corre\nsponding 1937 five-day period, giving\na decrease of 32 per cent. This com\npared with a loss of 23 per cent in\nthe similar comparison for the pre\nceding week.\nNew York clearings volume dropped\n39.2 per cent to $2,231,561,000 from\nthe $3,669,368,000 recorded last year,\nwhile the turnover at outside centers\nshrank to $1,572,896,000, a decline of\n18.2 per cent from the $1,921,788,000\nfor the same week a year ago.\nClearings for the latest week\ndropped $492,730,000 from the total j\nof the week preceding. This con-\ntrasted with a gain of $12,500,000 re-\nported for the two similar periods of i\n1937.\nAside from slight gains at Minne\napolis, Dallas and Portland, Oreg., all\noutside cities showed declines, the\nmore important of which were De\ntroit, 30.2 per cent; Boston, 28.8 per\ncent; Pittsburgh, 24.5 per cent;, Chi\ncago, 22.2 per cent; Louisville, 20.6\nper cent; Cleveland, 19.9 per cent;\nSan Francisco. 19.9 per cent, and\nBuffalo, 17.6 per cent.\nBank clearings at leading cites, to- j\ngether with percentage changes from\na year ago. follow. Also, the daily\naverage bank clearings for th\u00b0 months\nof December, January and February\nto date:\n(000 omitted.>\nWeek Pn\nfive day?) rent\nFeb. .\u20193 chance.\nBoston __ $i .v> 888 \u2014-s.fi\nPhiladelphia _ l\u2019Tk.oho \u201417..3,\nBuffalo _ 800 7 fi\nPittsburgh_ on.H57 .\u2014\u201d4 s\nCleveland _ tV2 333 \u2014]0 0\nCincinnati _ _ 4fi.ft7*: \u201417 3\nBaltimore _ ft].fi*?4 \u20141*2 fi\nRirnmond ___ .30.87 8 3 8\nAtlanta _ 4ft.4uo 8 3\nNew Orleans_ 33.88.3 *2.H\nChiraeo ___ *_'\u2022?(; *.'oo \u2014r'-\u00bb I\nDetroit fiS.33fi \u201430.C\nS'. Tiouis _ _ 7o.fi.ftft \u201413 7\nLouisville _ _ ?28.133 \u2014CO fi\nMinneapolis ftC.ooo 0 0\nKansas City _ 7ft.ft*23 \u201413 ft\nOmrha C3.HSC 0 0\nDa 11a 4 7 ft 4 0 ft\nSan Francisco _ 1 o7.1 7ft if* ri\nPortland. Oree. M.8fto o c\nSeattle *.\u20197.lft8 \u2014jn.4\nTo\u2019al _ Sl..ft7C8!>fi \u2014i fi c\nNew York __ C Cftl .fto! :;o s\nTo\u2018al all S3 804.3ft7 \u20143-77>\nAveraae daily:\nFebruary (to dat*0 S7<3 10\u2019 \"-ft\nJanuary 871.0!o jo \u00abi j\nDe ember OOC.ftos _17.C\n\nWHOLESALE INDEX\nDROPS TO NEW LOW\nFertilizer Asseciation Estimates\nAverage 76.3, Against 70.6 in\nPrevious Week.\nThe General level of wholesale rom- j\nmodify prires fell in the week ended\nFebruary 19 to a new low point for\nthe current recession, according to;\nthe index compiled by the National\nFertiliser Association. This index last\nweek stood at 76.3 per cent of th\u00bb\n1926-8 average, compared with 76.6\nin the preceding week. 77.8 a month\nago and 85.9 a year ago.\nFarm products and foods were gen\nerally higher during the wrok. but\nadvances in these groups were more\nthan offset by declines in other com\nmodities. The upturn in the food\nprice index was the first advance\nregistered by it in the past six weeks.\nIn the farm product group lower\nquotations for grains ar.d milk were\nmore than counterbalanced by rising\nprices for cotton and live stock. Cot\nton has now advanced for three con\nsecutive weeks and is back to the\nlevel of last September.\nA sharp decline in the price of\ngasoline at important refining centers\nwas responsible for the downturn in\nthe fuel price index, which is now i\nlower than at anv time since Janu\nary. 1937.\nIn the textile group higher prices\nfor cotton and silk offset the effect\nof declines in yarns, wool and hemp,\nwith the result that the group index\nremained unchanged.\nA decrease in lumber quotations\ncaused another downturn in the build\ning material index, which has been\nreceding since last spring.\nREVIVAL OF BUILDING\nHAILED IN FAR WEST\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nSAN FRANCISCO. Feb. 24.\u2014An\nupturn In western building activity\nduring January, following an eight\nmonth decline in this industry, pro\nvided an optimistic note to the current\nbusiness outlook, according to Bank\nof America's Business Review for the\nmonth of January, just released.\nThe value of permits issued in 50\nrepresentative cities in eight Western\nStates was $14,527,451, a gain of one\nthird over December and 5.5 per cent\nhigher than January, 1937.\nBank of America's index of Far\nWestern business for January, 1938,\nbased on carloadings, electric power\nproduction and bank debits, stands\nat 74 per cent of its computed normal.\nThis is 9.4 per oent under the index\nof the same month a year ago, and\n1.5 per cent below the figure of 75.1\nfor January, 1936. Compared with\nJanuary, 1935, this year\u2019s index shows\na gain of 14 per cent.\nValue of retail sales in 96 depart\nment and apparel stores in the twelfth\nFederal Reserve district showed a de\ncline of 4 per cent during January,\n1938, compared with the same month\nlast year.\nDEBITS TO INDIVIDUAL\nBANK ACCOUNTS GIVEN\nBy the Associated Press.\nDebits of individual accounts, re\nported by banks in leading cities for\nthe week ended February 16, totaled\n$7,066,000,000, or 10 per cent higher\nthan the preceding week and 20 per\ncent under last year, according to the\nFederal Reserve Board. The period\nincluded only five business days in\nmany reporting centers, the board\nsaid.\nDividend Boosted\nTo $1 Per Share\nBy Todd Shipyards\nBy the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK. Feb. 24.\u2014Todd Ship\nyards Corp. today declared a dividend\nof $1, payable March 21 to holders\nof record March 5. Last year the com\npany paid four 50-cent dividends and\na $3 special payment.\nElgin National Watch.\nElgin National Watch Co. declared\na dividend of 25 cents, payable March\n15 to holders of record March 4. Last,\nyear the company paid 50 cents each\nor. March 15, June 15 and September\n15, and $1.50 on December 15.\nBITUMINOUS OUTPUT\nOFF SLIGHTLY IN WEEK\nThe National Coal Association,\nfrom incomplete car-loading reports\nfrom the railroads, estimates bitumi\nnous coal production in the United\nStates for the week ended February 19\nas approximately 6.500,000 net tons.\nProduction for the corresponding\nweek: 1937, 10,840,000 tons; 1936,\n9,862,000 tons.\nThe report of the National Bi\ntuminous Coal Commission shows pro\nduction of 7,530.000 tons for the week\nended February 5 and 6,750,000 for the\nweek ended February 12, 1938.\nProduction calendar year to Feb\nruary 19: 1938, 49,407,000 tons (sub\nject to revision); corresponding period\n1937, 70,412,000 tons.\nI\n\nI\ni\n\nCONFECTIONERY SALES\nLAG BEHIND YEAR AGO\nBy the Associated Press.\nJanuary sales of confectionery and\nchocolate products by 282 manufac\nturers totaled 119,301,317, a decline\nof about 6 per cent from January,\n1937, the Department of Commerce\nreported.\n475 TONS OF LEAD SOLD.\nNEW YORK. Feb. 24 </F).\u2014Bt. Joseph\nLead Co. reports 475 tons of pi* lead\nfrom Southeast Missouri mines sold\nyesterday at $4.35 per 100 pounds, St.\nLouis.\nOFFICE FURNITURE\nWE SELL, BUY OR EXCHANGE\nChair* Steel File*\nDesks Steel Cabinet*\nTables Safes\nBAUM\u2019S OFFICE FURNITURE\n14ie Eye St. N.W. Phan* VA. SIM\nPAYMENTS TO\nHOLDERS OF\nFOREIGN RONDS\nMANY ISSUES OF FOREIGN\nBONDS ONCE IN COMPLETE DE\nFAULT HAVE NOW MADE PAR\nTIAL SETTLEMENTS OF BACK\nINTEREST OR HAVE RESUMED\nPARTIAL CURRENT PAYMENTS.\nHOLDERS DO NOT RECEIVE SUCH\nPAYMENTS AUTOMATICALLY BUT\nMI ST TAKE STEPS TO COLLECT\nTHEM. FAILURE TO COLLECT\nMAY. IN SOME CASES. CAUSE\nPERMANENT LOSS.\nIT IS OUR EXPERIENCE THAT\nALMOST EVERY HOLDER OF THE\nAVERAGE FOREIGN BONDS HAS\nITEMS OF COLLECTABLE INTER\nEST WHICH HAVE BEEN OVER\nLOOKED.\nWE SHALL BE GLAD TO RE\nVIEW YOUR HOLDINGS OF FOR\nEIGN BONDS. AND ASSIST IN THE\nCOLLECTION OF INTEREST DUE.\nWaggaman, Rrawner\n&C\u00ae. (Stic.\n1700 EYE X.W.\u2014ME. 3869\nFirst Mortgage Loan's\nDistrict of Columbia, Nearby Maryland and Virginia\nHomes Cf Qrf Business\nApartments Properties\nTerms from 3 to 15 years\nAlso\nMonthly Payment Loans\nRandall H.. Hag.ver St Company\nIMCO\u00abPO\u00bbATCO\nMortoaob Loan Correrpokobnt\nSkfe jfmuriinoe ^orryumy\n1321 Connecticut Are. N.W. T